Chapter 8 Hydraulic Fluids and Ancillary Devices

Cause of Hydraulic System problems

  • Clogged or dirty oil filters.
  • Inadequate supply oil in the reservoir.
  • Leaking Seals.
  • Loose inlet lines that cause the pump to take in air.
  • Incorrect type of oil.
  • Excessive oil temperature.
  • Excessive oil pressure.

50% of problems can traced directly to the oil and can be eliminated if a planned preventive maintenance program is undertaken.

Oxidation and Corrosion of Hydraulic Fluids

  • Oxidation is caused by the chemical reaction of oxygen from the oil with particles of oil, can seriously reduce the service life of a hydraulic fluid.
  • Most products of oxidation are soluble in oil and are acidic in nature, which can cause corrosion of parts throughout the system.
  • The products of oxidation include insoluble gums, sludge, and varnish, which tend to increase the viscosity of the oil.
  • Oxidation is most dramatically affected by temperature. The rate of oxidation is slower below 60 C but doubles for every 12 C temperature rise.
  • Additives are incorporated in many hydraulic oils to inhibit oxidation. Since this increases the cost, they should be specified only if necessary.
  • Rust is the chemical reaction between iron or steel and oxygen.
  • Corrosion is the chemical reaction between a metal and acid.
  • Rusting and corrosion causes excessive leakage past the sealing surface of the affected parts.
  • Rust and corrosion can be resisted by incorporating additives that plate on the metal surface to prevent chemical reaction.

Fire-resistant fluids

  • A fire-resistant fluid is one that can be ignited but will not support combustion when the ignition source is removed.
  • Flammability is defined as the ease of ignition and ability to propagate a flame.
  • The usual characteristics tested to determine the flammability of a hydraulic fluid are:
    • Flash point the temperature at which the oil surface gives off sufficient vapors to ignite when a flame is passed over the surface.
    • Fire point- the temperature at which the oil will release sufficient vapor to support combustion continuously for 5 seconds when a flame is passed over the surface.
    • Autogenous ignition temperature (AIT) the temperature at which ignition occurs spontaneously.

4 common types include:

1. Water Glycol Solutions

  • 40% water and 60% glycol. high viscosity index values but the viscosity rises as the water evaporates.
  • Operating temperature range runs from -20 C to about 80 C.
  • Metal such as zinc, cadmium, and magnesium react with water-glycol solutions and should not be used.

2. Water-in-oil emulsions

  • 40% water completely dispersed in a special oil base i.e. small droplets of water completely surrounded by oil.
  • Good coolant property but more corrosive.
  • Operating temperature range runs from -30 C to about 80 C.
  • Necessary to replenish evaporated water to maintain proper viscosity.
  • Compatible with most rubber seal materials.

3. Synthetics

  • formulated to inhibit combustion and in general has the highest fire-resistant temperature.
  • phosphate esters or chlorinated hydro-carbons.
  • low viscosity index, incompatible with most natural or synthetic rubber seals, and high cost.

4. High-water-content fluids

  • 90% water and 10% fluid additives that improve viscosity, lubricity, rust protection, and protection against bacteria growth.
  • high fire resistance, high cooling capacity, low cost.
  • Maximum operating temperature 50 C to minimize evaporation.
  • Compatible with most rubber seal materials

Entrained air

  • Air entering the fluid line can come in from a return line discharging above the oil level, leak in the conductor, and air pockets in high points in the system.
  • Entrained air in the fluid line can cause cavitation and reduction in bulk modulus.
  • A properly designed reservoir can greatly reduce these problems.

Fluid neutralisation number

The neutralization number is a measure of the relative acidity or alkalinity of a
hydraulic fluid and is specified by a pH factor. A fluid having a small neutralisation number is recommended because high acidity or alkalinity causes corrosion of
metal parts as well as deterioration of seals and packing glands. For an acidic fluid, the neutralization number equals the number of milligrams (mg) of potassium hydroxide necessary to neutralize the acid in a 1-g sample of the fluid.

Usage and disposal of hydraulic fluids

The following recommendations should be adhered to for properly maintaining and disposing of hydraulic fluids:

  • Select the optimum fluid for application involved. This includes consideration of the system operating pressure and temperature, as well as the desired fluid properties of specific gravity, viscosity, oxidation resistance and bulk modulus.
  • Use a well designed filtration system to reduce contamination and increase the useful life of the fluid. Filtration should be continuous and filters should be changed at regular interval.
  • Follow proper storage procedures for the unused fluid supply.
  • Transporting the fluids from the storage containers to the hydraulic systems should be done carefully, since the chances for contamination increase greatly with handling. Any transfer container used to deliver fluid from the storage drums or tanks to the hydraulic systems should be clearly labeled.
  • Operating fluids should be checked regularly for viscosity, acidity, bulk modulus, specific gravity, water content, additive levels, concentration of metals, and particle contamination.
  • The entire hydraulic system, including pumps, piping, fittings, valves, solenoids filters, actuator, and the reservoir, should be maintained according to manufacturers specifications.
  • Corrective action should be taken to reduce or eliminate leakage from operating hydraulic systems. A preventive maintenance program should be implemented to check seals, fitting and other equipment operating conditions.
  • Disposal of fluids must be done properly; with a certified contractor, because a hydraulic fluid is considered to be waste material when it has deteriorated to the point where it is no longer suitable for use in hydraulic system.

Ancillary Devices

Reservoir

Reservoirs serve multiple functions, mainly:

  • sedimentation of particulates
  • allowing entrained air to escape
  • prevent localised turbulence
  • heat transfer
    The rule of thumb for reservoir sizing is 3 times the expected pump flow rate per minute.

Accumulator

Accumulators have several uses, mainly:

  • auxiliary power source
    • to provide periodic increases in flow rate
  • leakage compensator
    • maintain pressure in a system
  • emergency power source
    • provide power in the case of system failure
  • shock absorber
    • absorb spikes in system pressure

The simplest kind of accumulator is the weight-loaded accumulator, where the force of gravity provides

Fluid Cleanliness

Filters

There are 3 types of filtering methods:

  1. Mechanical. Particles are blocked by the filtering material; traps coarse particles.
  2. Absorbent. Particles enter the filtering material; traps water and smaller particles.
  3. Adsorbent. Particles cling to the surface of the filter; traps gasses and microscopic particles.
  • Strainers are constructed of a wire screen wrapped around a metal frame. Strainers are only suitable for larger particles.
  • Because strainers have low pressure drops, they are usually installed in the pump suction line to remove contaminants large enough to damage the pump. A pressure gauge is normally installed in the suction line between the pump and strainer to indicate the condition of the strainer.

(a) shows a proportional flow filters are exposed to only a percentage of the total system flow during operation. It is assumed that on a recirculating basis the probability of mixture of the fluid within the system will force all the fluid through the proportional flow filter. The primary disadvantages of proportional flow filtration are that there is no positive protection of any specific components within the system, and there is no way to know when the filter is dirty.

(b), (c), and (d) show locations for full flow filtration filters, which accept all the flow of the pump.

  • The basic rule of thumb to consider where the dirt enters the system, and put the filter/filters where they are most effective. Good hydraulic system have multiple filters. - There should always be a filter in the inlet line and high pressure filter in the pump discharge line.
  • Placing the pump discharge filter between the pump and the pressure relief valve can provide very good filtration because oil is flowing through the filter even when the working part of the circuit is inactive and the pump discharge is going directly to the reservoir.

Wear due to contaminants

Solid contaminants can be classified by their size relative to the clearance between the moving parts of a hydraulic component. They are three relative sizes: smaller than, equal to and larger than the clearance. All three contaminant size can contribute to wear problems.

Contaminants that are smaller than the clearance can collect inside the clearance when the cylinder is not operating. These contaminants block lubricant flow through the clearance when actuation is initiated.

Contaminants of the same size as the clearance rub against the mating surfaces, causing a breakdown in the fluid lubricating film.

Larger contaminants interfere with lubrication by collecting at the entrance to the clearance and blocking fluid flow between the mating surface.

Troubleshooting hydraulic systems

  1. Noisy Pump
  • Air entering pump inlet.
  • Misalignment of pump and drive unit.
  • Excessive oil viscosity.
  • Dirty inlet strainer.
  • Chattering relief valve.
  • Damaged pump.
  • Excessive pump speed.
  • Loose or damaged inlet line.
  1. Low or erratic pressure
  • Air in the fluid.
  • Pressure relief valve set too slow.
  • Pressure relief valve not properly seated.
  • Leak in hydraulic line.
  • Defective or worn pump.
  • Defective or worn actuator.
  1. Actuator fails to move
  • Faulty pump.
  • Directional control valve fails to shift.
  • Defective actuator.
  • System pressure too low.
  • Pressure relief valve stuck open.
  • Actuator load is excessive.
  • Check valve installed backwards.
  1. Slow or erratic motion of actuator
  • Air in system.
  • Viscosity of fluid too high.
  • Worn or damaged pump.
  • Pump speed too slow.
  • Excessive leakage through actuators or valves.
  • Faulty or dirty flow control valves.
  • Blocked air breather in reservoir.
  • Low fluid level in reservoir.
  • Faulty check valve.
  • Defective pressure relief valve.
  1. No pressure
  • Pump turning in wrong direction.
  • Ruptured hydraulic line.
  • Low oil level in reservoir.
  • Pressure relief valve stuck open.
  • Broken pump shaft.
  • Full pump flow bypassed to tank due to faulty valve or actuator.
  1. Overheating of hydraulic fluid
  • Heat exchanger turned off or faulty.
  • Undersized components or piping.
  • Incorrect fluid.
  • Continuous operation of pressure relief valve.
  • Overloaded system.
  • Dirty fluid.
  • Reservoir too small.
  • Inadequate supply of oil in reservoir.
  • Excessive pump speed.
  • Clogged or inadequate-sized air breather.
